"{\"type\": \"event\", \"name\": \"The Battle of the Standards: The Election of 1896\", \"description\": \"The pivotal U.S. presidential election symbolizing the clash between agrarian silver interests and urban gold interests.\", \"introduction\": \"The 1896 U.S. presidential election marks a defining moment in American political history, showcasing a deep economic and cultural divide. It set the stage for the Fourth Party System and modern American politics. Leading up to the event, America was mired in economic depression, with debates raging over bimetallism versus the gold standard.\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-06-18\", \"end\": \"1896-11-03\"}, \"sections\": [{\"name\": \"Prelude to the Election\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1893-01-01\", \"end\": \"1896-06-17\"}, \"summary\": \"The Panic of 1893 triggered a severe economic depression in the United States. Issues of currency and bimetallism rose to prominence, with the 'Free Silver' movement advocating for the coinage of silver in addition to gold to inflate the currency and ease debts.\"}, {\"name\": \"Democratic National Convention\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-07-07\", \"end\": \"1896-07-11\"}, \"summary\": \"The Democratic Party nominated William Jennings Bryan after his impassioned 'Cross of Gold' speech, which championed the Free Silver cause and criticized the gold standard, resonating with struggling farmers and workers.\"}, {\"name\": \"Republican National Convention\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-06-18\", \"end\": \"1896-06-21\"}, \"summary\": \"The Republican Party nominated William McKinley, an advocate of protective tariffs and the gold standard. McKinley's campaign was managed by Mark Hanna, who ran a highly organized effort that capitalized on contributions from pro-gold business interests.\"}, {\"name\": \"Populist Party Convergence\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-07-24\", \"end\": \"1896-07-26\"}, \"summary\": \"The Populist Party, representing agrarian interests, chose to endorse Bryan despite some internal opposition. This move effectively merged their cause with that of the Democrats, further polarizing the silver vs. gold debate.\"}, {\"name\": \"The Campaign Strategies\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-07-01\", \"end\": \"1896-11-02\"}, \"summary\": \"Bryan embarked on a historic whistle-stop campaign, traveling widely and delivering hundreds of speeches. McKinley, conversely, conducted a 'front porch' campaign, giving speeches to visiting delegations at his home in Canton, Ohio, and emphasizing the stability of the gold standard.\"}, {\"name\": \"Election Day and Results\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-11-03\", \"end\": \"1896-11-03\"}, \"summary\": \"On November 3, 1896, the American electorate went to the polls. McKinley won the election, capturing the Northeast and Midwest, while Bryan won the South and the West. The results underscored the country's regional and economic divisions.\"}], \"conclusion\": \"The election of 1896 was a watershed moment that realigned American politics and solidified the gold standard until the Great Depression. It highlighted the divide between the industrial Northeast and Midwest and the agrarian South and West.\", \"people\": [{\"name\": \"William McKinley\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1843-01-29\", \"end\": \"1901-09-14\"}, \"description\": \"25th President of the United States, McKinley was a staunch supporter of the gold standard and won the 1896 election.\"}, {\"name\": \"William Jennings Bryan\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1860-03-19\", \"end\": \"1925-07-26\"}, \"description\": \"Democratic and Populist nominee for President in 1896, Bryan was a fervent advocate of the Free Silver movement.\"}, {\"name\": \"Mark Hanna\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1837-09-24\", \"end\": \"1904-02-15\"}, \"description\": \"An American industrialist and Republican senator, Hanna was the mastermind behind McKinley's successful presidential campaign.\"}, {\"name\": \"Thomas E. Watson\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1856-09-05\", \"end\": \"1922-09-26\"}, \"description\": \"A key Populist figure who initially opposed the merging of Populist and Democratic interests but later supported Bryan.\"}], \"places\": [{\"name\": \"Canton, Ohio\", \"description\": \"William McKinley's hometown where he conducted his 'front porch' campaign, symbolizing a calm, stable America.\"}, {\"name\": \"Chicago, Illinois\", \"description\": \"The site of the Democratic National Convention where Bryan delivered his famous 'Cross of Gold' speech.\"}, {\"name\": \"St. Louis, Missouri\", \"description\": \"The location of the Populist Party Convention where they decided to support Bryan for President.\"}, {\"name\": \"United States\", \"description\": \"The nation deeply divided by economic and regional issues, shaping the political landscape during the 1896 election.\"}], \"next\": [{\"name\": \"The Fourth Party System\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-01-01\", \"end\": \"1932-01-01\"}, \"description\": \"An era of American political history that began with the 1896 election, leading to the dominance of the Republican Party.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"The Panic of 1893\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1893-01-01\", \"end\": \"1897-01-01\"}, \"description\": \"The severe economic depression that led to the fierce debate over monetary policy in the United States.\", \"connection\": \"Cause\"}, {\"name\": \"Bryan's 'Cross of Gold' Speech\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-07-09\", \"end\": \"1896-07-09\"}, \"description\": \"An in-depth look at Bryan's influential speech and its impact on American politics and the Free Silver movement.\", \"connection\": \"Deep Dive\"}, {\"name\": \"Economic Policy Shifts in the Progressive Era\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1896-01-01\", \"end\": \"1920-01-01\"}, \"description\": \"An exploration of how the economic policies and debates from the 1896 election influenced subsequent reforms.\", \"connection\": \"Broad Perspective\"}, {\"name\": \"McKinley's Presidency and Policies\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1897-03-04\", \"end\": \"1901-09-14\"}, \"description\": \"A focus on McKinley's term in office, including his economic policies and the lead-up to his assassination.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"The Dingley Tariff of 1897\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1897-07-24\", \"end\": \"1897-07-24\"}, \"description\": \"A deep dive into the tariff legislation passed under McKinley and its impact on American trade policies.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"The Gold Standard Act of 1900\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1900-03-14\", \"end\": \"1900-03-14\"}, \"description\": \"The act that codified the gold standard, which was heavily debated in the 1896 election.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"Populism and Its Legacy\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1891-01-01\", \"end\": \"1896-12-31\"}, \"description\": \"An analysis of the Populist movement, its role in the 1896 election, and its lasting influence on American politics.\", \"connection\": \"Broad Perspective\"}]}"